# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: time-series-forecasting
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:time-series-forecasting/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] In time series analysis used in statistics and econometrics, **autoregressive integrated moving average** (**ARIMA**) and **seasonal ARIMA** (**SARIMA**) models are generalizations of the autoregressive moving average (ARMA) model to non-stationary series and periodic variation, respectively.
[src:time-series-forecasting/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] All these models are fitted to time series in order to better understand it and predict future values.
[src:time-series-forecasting/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] The purpose of these generalizations is to fit the data as well as possible.
[src:time-series-forecasting/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] Specifically, ARMA assumes that the series is stationary, that is, its expected value is constant in time.
[src:time-series-forecasting/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] If instead the series has a trend (but a constant variance/autocovariance), the trend is removed by "differencing", leaving a stationary series.
[src:time-series-forecasting/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] This operation generalizes ARMA and corresponds to the "integrated" part of ARIMA.
[src:time-series-forecasting/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] Analogously, periodic variation is removed by "seasonal differencing".
[src:time-series-forecasting/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] As in ARMA, the "autoregressive" (AR) part of ARIMA indicates that the evolving variable of interest is regressed on its prior values.
[src:time-series-forecasting/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] The "moving average" (MA) part indicates that the regression error is a linear combination of error terms whose values occurred contemporaneously and at various times in the past.
[src:time-series-forecasting/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] The "integrated" (I) part indicates that the data values have been replaced with the difference between each value and the previous value.
[src:time-series-forecasting/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] According to Wold's decomposition theorem the ARMA model is sufficient to describe a **regular** (a.k.a. purely nondeterministic) wide-sense stationary time series.
[src:time-series-forecasting/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] This motivates to make such a non-stationary time series stationary, e.g., by using differencing, before using ARMA.
[src:time-series-forecasting/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] If the time series contains a **predictable** sub-process (a.k.a. pure sine or complex-valued exponential process), the predictable component is treated as a non-zero-mean but periodic (i.e., seasonal) component in the ARIMA framework that it is eliminated by the seasonal differencing.
[src:time-series-forecasting/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] Seasonal ARIMA models are usually denoted by ARIMA(*p*, *d*, *q*)(*P*, *D*, *Q*)*m*, where the uppercase *P*, *D*, *Q* are the autoregressive, differencing, and moving average terms for the seasonal part of the ARIMA model, and *m* is the number of periods in each season.
[src:time-series-forecasting/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] When two of the parameters are 0, the model may be referred to based on the non-zero parameter, dropping "AR", "I" or "MA" from the acronym.
[src:time-series-forecasting/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] where L is the lag operator, the $\alpha _{i}$ are the parameters of the autoregressive part of the model, the $\theta _{i}$ are the parameters of the moving average part and the $\varepsilon _{t}$ are error terms.
[src:time-series-forecasting/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] The error terms $\varepsilon _{t}$ are generally assumed to be independent, identically distributed variables sampled from a normal distribution with zero mean.
[src:time-series-forecasting/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] and so is special case of an ARMA(*p+d*, *q*) process having the autoregressive polynomial with *d* unit roots.
[src:time-series-forecasting/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] The above can be generalized as follows.
[src:time-series-forecasting/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] The explicit identification of the factorization of the autoregression polynomial into factors as above can be extended to other cases, firstly to apply to the moving average polynomial and secondly to include other special factors.
[src:time-series-forecasting/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] For example, having a factor $(1-L^{s})$ in a model is one way of including a non-stationary seasonality of period *s* into the model; this factor has the effect of re-expressing the data as changes from *s* periods ago.
[src:time-series-forecasting/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] Another example is the factor $\left(1-{\sqrt {3}}L+L^{2}\right)$ , which includes a (non-stationary) seasonality of period 2.
[src:time-series-forecasting/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] The effect of the first type of factor is to allow each season's value to drift separately over time, whereas with the second type values for adjacent seasons move together.
[src:time-series-forecasting/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] A stationary time series's properties do not change.
[src:time-series-forecasting/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] Specifically, for a wide-sense stationary time series, the mean and the variance/autocovariance are constant over time.
[src:time-series-forecasting/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] **Differencing** in statistics is a transformation applied to a non-stationary time-series in order to make it trend stationary (i.e., stationary *in the mean sense*), by removing or subtracting the trend or non-constant mean.
[src:time-series-forecasting/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] However, it does not affect the non-stationarity of the variance or autocovariance.
[src:time-series-forecasting/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] Likewise, *seasonal differencing* or *deseasonalization* is applied to a time-series to remove the seasonal component.
[src:time-series-forecasting/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] From the perspective of signal processing, especially the Fourier spectral analysis theory, the trend is a low-frequency part in the spectrum of a series, while the season is a periodic-frequency part.
[src:time-series-forecasting/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] Therefore, differencing is a high-pass (that is, low-stop) filter and the seasonal-differencing is a comb filter to suppress respectively the low-frequency trend and the periodic-frequency season in the spectrum domain (rather than directly in the time domain).
[src:time-series-forecasting/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] To difference the data, we compute the difference between consecutive observations.
[src:time-series-forecasting/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] Seasonal differencing involves computing the difference between an observation and the corresponding observation in the previous season e.g a year.
[src:time-series-forecasting/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] The differenced data are then used for the estimation of an ARMA model.
[src:time-series-forecasting/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] Some well-known special cases arise naturally or are mathematically equivalent to other popular forecasting models.
[src:time-series-forecasting/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] The order *p* and *q* can be determined using the sample autocorrelation function (ACF), partial autocorrelation function (PACF), and/or extended autocorrelation function (EACF) method.
[src:time-series-forecasting/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] Other alternative methods include AIC, BIC, etc.
[src:time-series-forecasting/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] To determine the order of a non-seasonal ARIMA model, a useful criterion is the Akaike information criterion (AIC).
[src:time-series-forecasting/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] where *L*is the likelihood of the data, *p*is the order of the autoregressive part and *q*is the order of the moving average part.
[src:time-series-forecasting/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] The *k* represents the intercept of the ARIMA model.
[src:time-series-forecasting/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] For AIC, if *k* = 1 then there is an intercept in the ARIMA model (*c*≠ 0) and if *k*= 0 then there is no intercept in the ARIMA model (*c*= 0).
[src:time-series-forecasting/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] The objective is to minimize the AIC, AICc or BIC values for a good model.
[src:time-series-forecasting/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] The lower the value of one of these criteria for a range of models being investigated, the better the model will suit the data.
[src:time-series-forecasting/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] The AIC and the BIC are used for two completely different purposes.
[src:time-series-forecasting/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] While the AIC tries to approximate models towards the reality of the situation, the BIC attempts to find the perfect fit.
[src:time-series-forecasting/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] The BIC approach is often criticized as there never is a perfect fit to real-life complex data; however, it is still a useful method for selection as it penalizes models more heavily for having more parameters than the AIC would.
[src:time-series-forecasting/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] AICc can only be used to compare ARIMA models with the same orders of differencing.
[src:time-series-forecasting/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] For ARIMAs with different orders of differencing, RMSE can be used for model comparison.
[src:time-series-forecasting/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] The ARIMA model can be viewed as a "cascade" of two models.
[src:time-series-forecasting/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] Now forecasts can be made for the process $Y_{t}$ , using a generalization of the method of autoregressive forecasting.
[src:time-series-forecasting/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] The forecast intervals (confidence intervals for forecasts) for ARIMA models are based on assumptions that the residuals are uncorrelated and normally distributed.
[src:time-series-forecasting/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] If either of these assumptions does not hold, then the forecast intervals may be incorrect.
[src:time-series-forecasting/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] For this reason, researchers plot the ACF and histogram of the residuals to check the assumptions before producing forecast intervals.
[src:time-series-forecasting/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] For $h=1$ , $v_{T+h\,\mid \,T}={\hat {\sigma }}^{2}$ for all ARIMA models regardless of parameters and orders.
[src:time-series-forecasting/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] In general, forecast intervals from ARIMA models will increase as the forecast horizon increases.
[src:time-series-forecasting/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] A number of variations on the ARIMA model are commonly employed.
[src:time-series-forecasting/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] If multiple time series are used then the $X_{t}$ can be thought of as vectors and a VARIMA model may be appropriate.
[src:time-series-forecasting/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] Sometimes a seasonal effect is suspected in the model; in that case, it is generally considered better to use a SARIMA (seasonal ARIMA) model than to increase the order of the AR or MA parts of the model.
[src:time-series-forecasting/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] If the time-series is suspected to exhibit long-range dependence, then the *d* parameter may be allowed to have non-integer values in an autoregressive fractionally integrated moving average model, which is also called a Fractional ARIMA (FARIMA or ARFIMA) model.
[src:time-series-forecasting/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] Various packages that apply methodology like Box–Jenkins parameter optimization are available to find the right parameters for the ARIMA model.
[src:time-series-forecasting/exponential-smoothing] Exponential smoothing is one of many window functions commonly applied to smooth data in signal processing, acting as low-pass filters to remove high-frequency noise.
[src:time-series-forecasting/exponential-smoothing] This method is preceded by Poisson's use of recursive exponential window functions in convolutions from the 19th century, as well as Kolmogorov and Zurbenko's use of recursive moving averages from their studies of turbulence in the 1940s.
[src:time-series-forecasting/exponential-smoothing] where ${\textstyle \alpha }$ is the *smoothing factor*, and ${\textstyle 0<\alpha <1}$ .
[src:time-series-forecasting/exponential-smoothing] The use of the exponential window function is first attributed to Poisson as an extension of a numerical analysis technique from the 17th century, and later adopted by the signal processing community in the 1940s.
[src:time-series-forecasting/exponential-smoothing] Here, exponential smoothing is the application of the exponential, or Poisson, window function.
[src:time-series-forecasting/exponential-smoothing] Exponential smoothing was suggested in the statistical literature without citation to previous work by Robert Goodell Brown in 1956, and expanded by Charles C.
[src:time-series-forecasting/exponential-smoothing] The formulation below, which is the one commonly used, is attributed to Brown and is known as "Brown’s simple exponential smoothing".
[src:time-series-forecasting/exponential-smoothing] All the methods of Holt, Winters, and Brown may be seen as a simple application of recursive filtering, first found in the 1940s to convert finite impulse response (FIR) filters to infinite impulse response filters.
[src:time-series-forecasting/exponential-smoothing] where $\alpha$ is the *smoothing factor*, with $0\leq \alpha \leq 1$ .
[src:time-series-forecasting/exponential-smoothing] In other words, the smoothed statistic $s_{t}$ is a simple weighted average of the current observation $x_{t}$ and the previous smoothed statistic $s_{t-1}$ .
[src:time-series-forecasting/exponential-smoothing] Simple exponential smoothing is easily applied, and it produces a smoothed statistic as soon as two observations are available.
[src:time-series-forecasting/exponential-smoothing] The term *smoothing factor* applied to $\alpha$ here is something of a misnomer, as larger values of $\alpha$ actually reduce the level of smoothing, and in the limiting case with $\alpha$ = 1 the smoothing output series is just the current observation.
[src:time-series-forecasting/exponential-smoothing] Values of $\alpha$ close to 1 have less of a smoothing effect and give greater weight to recent changes in the data, while values of $\alpha$ closer to 0 have a greater smoothing effect and are less responsive to recent changes.
[src:time-series-forecasting/exponential-smoothing] In the limiting case with $\alpha$ = 0, the output series is just flat or a constant as the observation ${\textstyle x_{0}}$ at the beginning of the smoothening process ${\textstyle t=0}$ .
[src:time-series-forecasting/exponential-smoothing] The method for choosing $\alpha$ must be decided by the modeler.
[src:time-series-forecasting/exponential-smoothing] Sometimes the statistician's judgment is used to choose an appropriate factor.
[src:time-series-forecasting/exponential-smoothing] Alternatively, a statistical technique may be used to *optimize* the value of $\alpha$ .
[src:time-series-forecasting/exponential-smoothing] For example, the method of least squares might be used to determine the value of $\alpha$ for which the sum of the quantities $(s_{t}-x_{t+1})^{2}$ is minimized.
[src:time-series-forecasting/exponential-smoothing] Unlike some other smoothing methods, such as the simple moving average, this technique does not require any minimum number of observations to be made before it begins to produce results.
[src:time-series-forecasting/exponential-smoothing] In practice, however, a "good average" will not be achieved until several samples have been averaged together; for example, a constant signal will take approximately $3/\alpha$ stages to reach 95% of the actual value.
[src:time-series-forecasting/exponential-smoothing] To accurately reconstruct the original signal without information loss, all stages of the exponential moving average must also be available, because older samples decay in weight exponentially.
[src:time-series-forecasting/exponential-smoothing] This is in contrast to a simple moving average, in which some samples can be skipped without as much loss of information due to the constant weighting of samples within the average.
[src:time-series-forecasting/exponential-smoothing] If a known number of samples will be missed, one can adjust a weighted average for this as well, by giving equal weight to the new sample and all those to be skipped.
[src:time-series-forecasting/exponential-smoothing] This simple form of exponential smoothing is also known as an exponentially weighted moving average (EWMA).
[src:time-series-forecasting/exponential-smoothing] Technically it can also be classified as an autoregressive integrated moving average (ARIMA) (0,1,1) model with no constant term.
[src:time-series-forecasting/exponential-smoothing] The time constant of an exponential moving average is the amount of time for the smoothed response of a unit step function to reach $1-1/e\approx 63.2\,\%$ of the final signal.
[src:time-series-forecasting/exponential-smoothing] where $\Delta T$ is the sampling time interval of the discrete time implementation.
[src:time-series-forecasting/exponential-smoothing] Note that in the definition above, $s_{0}$ (the initial output of the exponential smoothing algorithm) is being initialized to $x_{0}$ (the initial raw data or observation).
[src:time-series-forecasting/exponential-smoothing] Because exponential smoothing requires that, at each stage, we have the previous forecast $s_{t-1}$ , it is not obvious how to get the method started.
[src:time-series-forecasting/exponential-smoothing] We could assume that the initial forecast is equal to the initial value of demand; however, this approach has a serious drawback.
[src:time-series-forecasting/exponential-smoothing] Exponential smoothing puts substantial weight on past observations, so the initial value of demand will have an unreasonably large effect on early forecasts.
[src:time-series-forecasting/exponential-smoothing] This problem can be overcome by allowing the process to evolve for a reasonable number of periods (10 or more) and using the average of the demand during those periods as the initial forecast.
[src:time-series-forecasting/exponential-smoothing] There are many other ways of setting this initial value, but the smaller the value of $\alpha$ , the more sensitive the forecast will be on the selection of this initial smoother value $s_{0}$ .
[src:time-series-forecasting/exponential-smoothing] For every exponential smoothing method, we also need to choose the value for the smoothing parameters.
[src:time-series-forecasting/exponential-smoothing] For simple exponential smoothing, there is only one smoothing parameter (*α*), but for the methods that follow there are usually more than one smoothing parameter.
[src:time-series-forecasting/exponential-smoothing] There are cases where the smoothing parameters may be chosen in a subjective manner – the forecaster specifies the value of the smoothing parameters based on previous experience.
[src:time-series-forecasting/exponential-smoothing] However, a more robust and objective way to obtain values of the unknown parameters included in any exponential smoothing method is to estimate them from the observed data.
[src:time-series-forecasting/exponential-smoothing] The unknown parameters and the initial values for any exponential smoothing method can be estimated by minimizing the sum of squared errors (SSE).
[src:time-series-forecasting/exponential-smoothing] Unlike the regression case (where we have formulae to directly compute the regression coefficients which minimize the SSE) this involves a non-linear minimization problem, and we need to use an optimization tool to perform this.
[src:time-series-forecasting/exponential-smoothing] The name *exponential smoothing* is attributed to the use of the exponential function as the filter impulse response in the convolution.
[src:time-series-forecasting/exponential-smoothing] A geometric progression is the discrete version of an exponential function, so this is where the name for this smoothing method originated according to Statistics lore.
[src:time-series-forecasting/exponential-smoothing] Exponential smoothing and moving average have similar defects of introducing a lag relative to the input data.
[src:time-series-forecasting/exponential-smoothing] While this can be corrected by shifting the result by half the window length for a symmetrical kernel, such as a moving average or gaussian, this approach is not possible for exponential smoothing since it is an IIR filter and therefore has an asymmetric kernel and frequency-dependent group delay.
[src:time-series-forecasting/exponential-smoothing] This means each constituent frequency is shifted by a different amount and therefore, there is no single number of samples that can be used to shift the output signal to account for the lag.
[src:time-series-forecasting/exponential-smoothing] Both filters also both have roughly the same distribution of forecast error when *α* = 2/(*k* + 1) where *k* is the number of past data points in consideration of moving average.
[src:time-series-forecasting/exponential-smoothing] They differ in that exponential smoothing takes into account all past data, whereas moving average only takes into account *k* past data points.
[src:time-series-forecasting/exponential-smoothing] Computationally speaking, they also differ in that moving average requires that the past *k* data points, or the data point at lag *k* + 1 plus the most recent forecast value, to be kept, whereas exponential smoothing only needs the most recent forecast value to be kept.
[src:time-series-forecasting/exponential-smoothing] Simple exponential smoothing does not do well when there is a trend in the data.
[src:time-series-forecasting/exponential-smoothing] In such situations, several methods were devised under the name "double exponential smoothing" or "second-order exponential smoothing," which is the recursive application of an exponential filter twice, thus being termed "double exponential smoothing".
[src:time-series-forecasting/exponential-smoothing] The basic idea behind double exponential smoothing is to introduce a term to take into account the possibility of a series exhibiting some form of trend.
[src:time-series-forecasting/exponential-smoothing] This slope component is itself updated via exponential smoothing.
[src:time-series-forecasting/exponential-smoothing] Again, the raw data sequence of observations is represented by $x_{t}$ , beginning at time $t=0$ .
[src:time-series-forecasting/exponential-smoothing] We use $s_{t}$ to represent the smoothed value for time t , and $b_{t}$ is our best estimate of the trend at time t .
[src:time-series-forecasting/exponential-smoothing] The output of the algorithm is now written as $F_{t+m}$ , an estimate of the value of $x_{t+m}$ at time $m>0$ based on the raw data up to time t .
[src:time-series-forecasting/exponential-smoothing] where $\alpha$ ( $0\leq \alpha \leq 1$ ) is the *data smoothing factor*, and $\beta$ ( $0\leq \beta \leq 1$ ) is the *trend smoothing factor*.
[src:time-series-forecasting/exponential-smoothing] Setting the initial value b is a matter of preference.
[src:time-series-forecasting/exponential-smoothing] An option other than the one listed above is ${\textstyle {\frac {x_{n}-x_{0}}{n}}}$ for some n .
[src:time-series-forecasting/exponential-smoothing] Note that *F*0 is undefined (there is no estimation for time 0), and according to the definition *F*1=*s*0+*b*0, which is well defined, thus further values can be evaluated.
[src:time-series-forecasting/exponential-smoothing] Triple exponential smoothing applies exponential smoothing three times, which is commonly used when there are three high frequency signals to be removed from a time series under study.
[src:time-series-forecasting/exponential-smoothing] There are different types of seasonality: 'multiplicative' and 'additive' in nature.
[src:time-series-forecasting/exponential-smoothing] Multiplicative signifies that the seasonal effect size depends on the current level, while additive seasonal effects do not.
[src:time-series-forecasting/exponential-smoothing] If in *every* summer we sell 10,000 more balls of ice cream than we do in winter, then seasonality is *additive*.
[src:time-series-forecasting/exponential-smoothing] However, if we sell 6 times more ice cream in summer than in winter, that means that the difference in sales amounts moves together with the level itself: in years with overall larger consumption, the difference between summer and winter is larger and vice versa.
[src:time-series-forecasting/exponential-smoothing] Multiplicative seasonality can be represented as a constant factor, additive seasonality as an absolute amount.
[src:time-series-forecasting/exponential-smoothing] Triple exponential smoothing was first suggested by Holt's student, Peter Winters, in 1960 after reading a signal processing book from the 1940s on exponential smoothing.
[src:time-series-forecasting/exponential-smoothing] Holt's novel idea was to repeat filtering an odd number of times greater than 1 and less than 5, which was popular with scholars of previous eras.
[src:time-series-forecasting/exponential-smoothing] While recursive filtering had been used previously, it was applied twice and four times to coincide with the Hadamard conjecture, while triple application required more than double the operations of singular convolution.
[src:time-series-forecasting/exponential-smoothing] The use of a triple application is considered a rule of thumb technique, rather than one based on theoretical foundations and has often been overemphasized by practitioners.
[src:time-series-forecasting/exponential-smoothing] Suppose we have a sequence of observations $x_{t},$ beginning at time $t=0$ with a cycle of seasonal change of length L .
[src:time-series-forecasting/exponential-smoothing] The method calculates a trend line for the data as well as seasonal indices that weight the values in the trend line based on where that time point falls in the cycle of length L .
[src:time-series-forecasting/exponential-smoothing] Let $s_{t}$ represent the smoothed value of the constant part for time t , $b_{t}$ is the sequence of best estimates of the linear trend that are superimposed on the seasonal changes, and $c_{t}$ is the sequence of seasonal correction factors.
[src:time-series-forecasting/exponential-smoothing] We wish to estimate $c_{t}$ at every time t mod L in the cycle that the observations take on.
[src:time-series-forecasting/exponential-smoothing] As a rule of thumb, a minimum of two full seasons (or $2L$ periods) of historical data is needed to initialize a set of seasonal factors.
[src:time-series-forecasting/exponential-smoothing] The output of the algorithm is again written as $F_{t+m}$ , an estimate of the value of $x_{t+m}$ at time $t+m>0$ based on the raw data up to time t .
[src:time-series-forecasting/exponential-smoothing] where $\alpha$ ( $0\leq \alpha \leq 1$ ) is the *data smoothing factor*, $\beta$ ( $0\leq \beta \leq 1$ ) is the *trend smoothing factor*, and $\gamma$ ( $0\leq \gamma \leq 1$ ) is the *seasonal change smoothing factor*.
[src:time-series-forecasting/exponential-smoothing] Setting the initial estimates for the seasonal indices $c_{i}$ for $i=1,2,\ldots ,L$ is a bit more involved.
[src:time-series-forecasting/exponential-smoothing] Note that $A_{j}$ is the average value of x in the $j^{\text{th}}$ cycle of your data.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] Risk and uncertainty are central to forecasting and prediction; it is generally considered a good practice to indicate the degree of uncertainty attaching to forecasts.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] In any case, the data must be up to date in order for the forecast to be as accurate as possible.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] In some cases the data used to predict the variable of interest is itself forecast.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] A forecast is not to be confused with a Budget; budgets are more specific, fixed-term financial plans used for resource allocation and control, while forecasts provide estimates of future financial performance, allowing for flexibility and adaptability to changing circumstances.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] Both tools are valuable in financial planning and decision-making, but they serve different functions.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] Forecasting has applications in a wide range of fields where estimates of future conditions are useful.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] Depending on the field, accuracy varies significantly.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] If the factors that relate to what is being forecast are known and well understood and there is a significant amount of data that can be used, it is likely the final value will be close to the forecast.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] If this is not the case or if the actual outcome is affected by the forecasts, the reliability of the forecasts can be significantly lower.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] Climate change and increasing energy prices have led to the use of Egain Forecasting for buildings.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] This attempts to reduce the energy needed to heat the building, thus reducing the emission of greenhouse gases.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] Forecasting is used in customer demand planning in everyday business for manufacturing and distribution companies.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] While the veracity of predictions for actual stock returns are disputed through reference to the efficient-market hypothesis, forecasting of broad economic trends is common.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] Such analysis is provided by both non-profit groups as well as by for-profit private institutions.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] Forecasting foreign exchange movements is typically achieved through a combination of historical and current data (summarized in charts) and fundamental analysis.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] An essential difference between chart analysis and fundamental economic analysis is that chartists study only the price action of a market, whereas fundamentalists attempt to look to the reasons behind the action.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] Financial institutions assimilate the evidence provided by their fundamental and chartist researchers into one note to provide a final projection on the currency in question.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] Forecasting has also been used to predict the development of conflict situations.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] Forecasters perform research that uses empirical results to gauge the effectiveness of certain forecasting models.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] However research has shown that there is little difference between the accuracy of the forecasts of experts knowledgeable in the conflict situation and those by individuals who knew much less.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] Similarly, experts in some studies argue that role thinking — standing in other people's shoes to forecast their decisions — does not contribute to the accuracy of the forecast.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] An important, albeit often ignored aspect of forecasting, is the relationship it holds with planning.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] Forecasting can be described as predicting what the future *will* look like, whereas planning predicts what the future *should* look like.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] There is no single right forecasting method to use.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] Selection of a method should be based on your objectives and your conditions (data etc.).
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] A good way to find a method is by visiting a selection tree.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] An example of a selection tree can be found here.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] In several cases, the forecast is either more or less than a prediction of the future.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] Tetlock's *Superforecasting: The Art and Science of Prediction*, he discusses forecasting as a method of improving the ability to make decisions.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] A person can become better calibrated — *i.e.* having things they give 10% credence to happening 10% of the time.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] Or they can forecast things more confidently — coming to the same conclusion but earlier.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] Some have claimed that forecasting is a transferable skill with benefits to other areas of discussion and decision making.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] Betting on sports or politics is another form of forecasting.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] Rather than being used as advice, bettors are paid based on if they predicted correctly.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] While decisions might be made based on these bets (forecasts), the main motivation is generally financial.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] Finally, futarchy is a form of government where forecasts of the impact of government action are used to decide which actions are taken.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] Rather than advice, in futarchy's strongest form, the action with the best forecasted result is automatically taken.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] Forecast improvement projects have been operated in a number of sectors: the National Hurricane Center's Hurricane Forecast Improvement Project (HFIP) and the Wind Forecast Improvement Project sponsored by the US Department of Energy are examples.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] In relation to supply chain management, the Du Pont model has been used to show that an increase in forecast accuracy can generate increases in sales and reductions in inventory, operating expenses and commitment of working capital.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] Qualitative forecasting techniques are subjective, based on the opinion and judgment of consumers and experts; they are appropriate when past data are not available.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] They are usually applied to intermediate- or long-range decisions.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] Examples of qualitative forecasting methods are informed opinion and judgment, the Delphi method, market research, and historical life-cycle analogy.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] Quantitative forecasting models are used to forecast future data as a function of past data.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] They are appropriate to use when past numerical data is available and when it is reasonable to assume that some of the patterns in the data are expected to continue into the future.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] These methods are usually applied to short- or intermediate-range decisions.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] Examples of quantitative forecasting methods are last period demand, simple and weighted N-Period moving averages, simple exponential smoothing, Poisson process model based forecasting and multiplicative seasonal indexes.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] Previous research shows that different methods may lead to different level of forecasting accuracy.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] For example, GMDH neural network was found to have better forecasting performance than the classical forecasting algorithms such as Single Exponential Smooth, Double Exponential Smooth, ARIMA and back-propagation neural network.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] In this approach, the predictions of all future values are equal to the mean of the past data.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] This approach can be used with any sort of data where past data is available.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] Although the time series notation has been used here, the average approach can also be used for cross-sectional data (when we are predicting unobserved values; values that are not included in the data set).
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] Then, the prediction for unobserved values is the average of the observed values.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] Naïve forecasts are the most cost-effective forecasting model, and provide a benchmark against which more sophisticated models can be compared.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] This forecasting method is only suitable for time series data.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] Using the naïve approach, forecasts are produced that are equal to the last observed value.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] This method works quite well for economic and financial time series, which often have patterns that are difficult to reliably and accurately predict.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] If the time series is believed to have seasonality, the seasonal naïve approach may be more appropriate where the forecasts are equal to the value from last season.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] A variation on the naïve method is to allow the forecasts to increase or decrease over time, where the amount of change over time (called the drift) is set to be the average change seen in the historical data.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] This is equivalent to drawing a line between the first and last observation, and extrapolating it into the future.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] The seasonal naïve method accounts for seasonality by setting each prediction to be equal to the last observed value of the same season.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] For example, the prediction value for all subsequent months of April will be equal to the previous value observed for April.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] where m is the seasonal period (for example, for monthly data with yearly seasonality, $m=12$ ) and k is the integer part of $(h-1)/m$ .
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] The seasonal naïve method is particularly useful for data that has a very high level of seasonality.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] A deterministic approach is when there is no stochastic variable involved and the forecasts depend on the selected functions and parameters.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] where $\alpha ,\gamma ,\beta ,\mu ,\eta$ are some parameters.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] This approach has been proposed to simulate bursts of seemingly stochastic activity, interrupted by quieter periods.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] The assumption is that the presence of a strong deterministic ingredient is hidden by noise.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] The deterministic approach is noteworthy as it can reveal the underlying dynamical systems structure, which can be exploited for steering the dynamics into a desired regime.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] Time series methods use historical data as the basis of estimating future outcomes.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] They are based on the assumption that past demand history is a good indicator of future demand.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] Some forecasting methods try to identify the underlying factors that might influence the variable that is being forecast.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] For example, including information about climate patterns might improve the ability of a model to predict umbrella sales.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] Forecasting models often take account of regular seasonal variations.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] In addition to climate, such variations can also be due to holidays and customs: for example, one might predict that sales of college football apparel will be higher during the football season than during the off season.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] Several informal methods used in causal forecasting do not rely solely on the output of mathematical algorithms, but instead use the judgment of the forecaster.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] Quantitative forecasting models are often judged against each other by comparing their in-sample or out-of-sample mean square error, although some researchers have advised against this.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] Different forecasting approaches have different levels of accuracy.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] For example, it was found in one context that GMDH has higher forecasting accuracy than traditional ARIMA.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] Judgmental forecasting methods incorporate intuitive judgement, opinions and subjective probability estimates.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] Judgmental forecasting is used in cases where there is a lack of historical data or during completely new and unique market conditions.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] Can be created with 3 points of a sequence and the "moment" or "index".
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] This type of extrapolation has 100% accuracy in predictions in a big percentage of known series database (OEIS).
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] where E is the forecast error at period t, Y is the actual value at period t, and F is the forecast for period t.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] A good forecasting method will yield residuals that are **uncorrelated**.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] If there are correlations between residual values, then there is information left in the residuals which should be used in computing forecasts.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] This can be accomplished by computing the expected value of a residual as a function of the known past residuals, and adjusting the forecast by the amount by which this expected value differs from zero.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] A good forecasting method will also have **zero mean**.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] If the residuals have a mean other than zero, then the forecasts are biased and can be improved by adjusting the forecasting technique by an additive constant that equals the mean of the unadjusted residuals.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] The forecast error, E, is on the same scale as the data, as such, these accuracy measures are scale-dependent and cannot be used to make comparisons between series on different scales.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] These are more frequently used to compare forecast performance between different data sets because they are scale-independent.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] However, they have the disadvantage of being extremely large or undefined if Y is close to or equal to zero.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] Hyndman and Koehler (2006) proposed using scaled errors as an alternative to percentage errors.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] Business forecasters and practitioners sometimes use different terminology.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] They refer to the PMAD as the MAPE, although they compute this as a volume weighted MAPE.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] For more information, see Calculating demand forecast accuracy.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] When comparing the accuracy of different forecasting methods on a specific data set, the measures of aggregate error are compared with each other and the method that yields the lowest error is preferred.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] When evaluating the quality of forecasts, it is invalid to look at how well a model fits the historical data; the accuracy of forecasts can only be determined by considering how well a model performs on new data that were not used when fitting the model.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] When choosing models, it is common to use a portion of the available data for fitting, and use the rest of the data for testing the model, as was done in the above examples.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] Cross-validation is a more sophisticated version of training a test set.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] Repeat the above step for *i* = 1,2,..., *N* where *N* is the total number of observations.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] Compute the forecast accuracy measures based on the errors obtained.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] For time series data, the training set can only include observations prior to the test set.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] Therefore, no future observations can be used in constructing the forecast.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] Repeat the above step for *i* = 2,...,*T–k* where *T* is the total number of observations.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] Compute the forecast accuracy over all errors.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] This procedure is sometimes known as a "rolling forecasting origin" because the "origin" (*k+i -1)* at which the forecast is based rolls forward in time.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] Further, two-step-ahead or in general *p*-step-ahead forecasts can be computed by first forecasting the value immediately after the training set, then using this value with the training set values to forecast two periods ahead, etc.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] Some authors distinguish **forecastability** from **forecast accuracy**.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] In this usage, forecastability refers to the inherent predictability of a time series or process, while forecast accuracy refers to the performance of a particular forecasting method applied to it.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] Forecastability has also been discussed as a structural property of time series related to regularity and predictability.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] Seasonality is a characteristic of a time series in which the data experiences regular and predictable changes which recur every calendar year.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] Any predictable change or pattern in a time series that recurs or repeats over a one-year period can be said to be seasonal.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] It is common in many situations – such as grocery store or even in a Medical Examiner's office—that the demand depends on the day of the week.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] An index higher than 1 indicates that demand is higher than average; an index less than 1 indicates that the demand is less than the average.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] The cyclic behaviour of data takes place when there are regular fluctuations in the data which usually last for an interval of at least two years, and when the length of the current cycle cannot be predetermined.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] Cyclic behavior is not to be confused with seasonal behavior.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] Seasonal fluctuations follow a consistent pattern each year so the period is always known.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] As an example, during the Christmas period, inventories of stores tend to increase in order to prepare for Christmas shoppers.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] As an example of cyclic behaviour, the population of a particular natural ecosystem will exhibit cyclic behaviour when the population decreases as its natural food source decreases, and once the population is low, the food source will recover and the population will start to increase again.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] Cyclic data cannot be accounted for using ordinary seasonal adjustment since it is not of fixed period.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] Limitations pose barriers beyond which forecasting methods cannot reliably predict.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] There are many events and values that cannot be forecast reliably.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] Events such as the roll of a die or the results of the lottery cannot be forecast because they are random events and there is no significant relationship in the data.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] The concept of "self-destructing predictions" concerns the way in which some predictions can undermine themselves by influencing social behavior.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] This is because "predictors are part of the social context about which they are trying to make a prediction and may influence that context in the process".
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] For example, a forecast that a large percentage of a population will become HIV infected based on existing trends may cause more people to avoid risky behavior and thus reduce the HIV infection rate, invalidating the forecast (which might have remained correct if it had not been publicly known).
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] Or, a prediction that cybersecurity will become a major issue may cause organizations to implement more security cybersecurity measures, thus limiting the issue.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] As proposed by Edward Lorenz in 1963, long range weather forecasts, those made at a range of two weeks or more, are impossible to definitively predict the state of the atmosphere, owing to the chaotic nature of the fluid dynamics equations involved.
[src:time-series-forecasting/forecasting] Extremely small errors in the initial input, such as temperatures and winds, within numerical models double every five days.
[src:time-series-forecasting/long-short-term-memory] An LSTM unit is typically composed of a cell and three gates: an input gate, an output gate, and a forget gate.
[src:time-series-forecasting/long-short-term-memory] The cell remembers values over arbitrary time intervals, and the gates regulate the flow of information into and out of the cell.
[src:time-series-forecasting/long-short-term-memory] Forget gates decide what information to discard from the previous state, by mapping the previous state and the current input to a value between 0 and 1.
[src:time-series-forecasting/long-short-term-memory] A (rounded) value of 1 signifies retention of the information, and a value of 0 represents discarding.
[src:time-series-forecasting/long-short-term-memory] Input gates decide which pieces of new information to store in the current cell state, using the same system as forget gates.
[src:time-series-forecasting/long-short-term-memory] Output gates control which pieces of information in the current cell state to output, by assigning a value from 0 to 1 to the information, considering the previous and current states.
[src:time-series-forecasting/long-short-term-memory] Selectively outputting relevant information from the current state allows the LSTM network to maintain useful, long-term dependencies to make predictions, both in current and future time-steps.
[src:time-series-forecasting/long-short-term-memory] LSTM has wide applications in classification, data processing, time series analysis tasks, speech recognition, machine translation, speech activity detection, robot control, video games, healthcare, energy forecasting.
[src:time-series-forecasting/long-short-term-memory] In theory, classic RNNs can keep track of arbitrary long-term dependencies in the input sequences.
[src:time-series-forecasting/long-short-term-memory] RNNs using LSTM units partially solve the vanishing gradient problem, because LSTM units allow gradients to also flow with little to no attenuation.
[src:time-series-forecasting/long-short-term-memory] However, LSTM networks can still suffer from the exploding gradient problem.
[src:time-series-forecasting/long-short-term-memory] The intuition behind the LSTM architecture is to create an additional module in a neural network that learns when to remember and when to forget pertinent information.
[src:time-series-forecasting/long-short-term-memory] In other words, the network effectively learns which information might be needed later on in a sequence and when that information is no longer needed.
[src:time-series-forecasting/long-short-term-memory] For instance, in the context of natural language processing, the network can learn grammatical dependencies.
[src:time-series-forecasting/long-short-term-memory] An LSTM might process the sentence "Dave, as a result of his controversial claims, is now a pariah" by remembering the (statistically likely) grammatical gender and number of the subject *Dave*.
[src:time-series-forecasting/long-short-term-memory] Note that this information is pertinent for the pronoun *his* and note that this information is no longer important after the verb *is*.
[src:time-series-forecasting/long-short-term-memory] In the equations below, the lowercase variables represent vectors.
[src:time-series-forecasting/long-short-term-memory] Matrices $W_{q}$ and $U_{q}$ contain, respectively, the weights of the input and recurrent connections, where the subscript $_{q}$ can either be the input gate i , output gate o , the forget gate f or the memory cell c , depending on the activation being calculated.
[src:time-series-forecasting/long-short-term-memory] In this section, we are thus using a "vector notation".
[src:time-series-forecasting/long-short-term-memory] So, for example, $c_{t}\in \mathbb {R} ^{h}$ is not just one unit of one LSTM cell, but contains h LSTM cell's units.
[src:time-series-forecasting/long-short-term-memory] where the initial values are $c_{0}=0$ and $h_{0}=0$ and the operator $\odot$ denotes the Hadamard product (element-wise product).
[src:time-series-forecasting/long-short-term-memory] The figure on the right is a graphical representation of an LSTM unit with peephole connections (i.e. a peephole LSTM).
[src:time-series-forecasting/long-short-term-memory] Peephole connections allow the gates to access the constant error carousel (CEC), whose activation is the cell state. $h_{t-1}$ is not used, $c_{t-1}$ is used instead in most places.
[src:time-series-forecasting/long-short-term-memory] The 3 exit arrows from the memory cell c to the 3 gates $i,o$ and f represent the *peephole* connections.
[src:time-series-forecasting/long-short-term-memory] These peephole connections actually denote the contributions of the activation of the memory cell c at time step $t-1$ , i.e. the contribution of $c_{t-1}$ (and not $c_{t}$ , as the picture may suggest).
[src:time-series-forecasting/long-short-term-memory] In other words, the gates $i,o$ and f calculate their activations at time step t (i.e., respectively, $i_{t},o_{t}$ and $f_{t}$ ) also considering the activation of the memory cell c at time step $t-1$ , i.e. $c_{t-1}$ .
[src:time-series-forecasting/long-short-term-memory] The single left-to-right arrow exiting the memory cell is *not* a peephole connection and denotes $c_{t}$ .
[src:time-series-forecasting/long-short-term-memory] The little circles containing a $\times$ symbol represent an element-wise multiplication between its inputs.
[src:time-series-forecasting/long-short-term-memory] The big circles containing an *S*-like curve represent the application of a differentiable function (like the sigmoid function) to a weighted sum.
[src:time-series-forecasting/long-short-term-memory] A problem with using gradient descent for standard RNNs is that error gradients vanish exponentially quickly with the size of the time lag between important events.
[src:time-series-forecasting/long-short-term-memory] This is due to $\lim _{n\to \infty }W^{n}=0$ if the spectral radius of W is smaller than 1.
[src:time-series-forecasting/long-short-term-memory] However, with LSTM units, when error values are back-propagated from the output layer, the error remains in the LSTM unit's cell.
[src:time-series-forecasting/long-short-term-memory] This "error carousel" continuously feeds error back to each of the LSTM unit's gates, until they learn to cut off the value.
[src:time-series-forecasting/long-short-term-memory] Many applications use stacks of LSTM RNNs and train them by connectionist temporal classification (CTC) to find an RNN weight matrix that maximizes the probability of the label sequences in a training set, given the corresponding input sequences.
[src:time-series-forecasting/long-short-term-memory] CTC achieves both alignment and recognition.
[src:time-series-forecasting/long-short-term-memory] Sometimes, it can be advantageous to train (parts of) an LSTM by neuroevolution or by policy gradient methods, especially when there is no "teacher" (that is, training labels).
[src:time-series-forecasting/long-short-term-memory] Apple announced in its Worldwide Developers Conference that it would start using the LSTM for quicktype in the iPhone and for Siri.
[src:time-series-forecasting/long-short-term-memory] Amazon released Polly, which generates the voices behind Alexa, using a bidirectional LSTM for the text-to-speech technology.
[src:time-series-forecasting/long-short-term-memory] Microsoft reported reaching 94.9% recognition accuracy on the Switchboard corpus, incorporating a vocabulary of 165,000 words.
[src:time-series-forecasting/long-short-term-memory] The approach used "dialog session-based long-short-term memory".
[src:time-series-forecasting/long-short-term-memory] Aspects of LSTM were anticipated by "focused back-propagation", cited by the LSTM paper.
[src:time-series-forecasting/long-short-term-memory] Sepp Hochreiter's 1991 German diploma thesis analyzed the vanishing gradient problem and developed principles of the method.
[src:time-series-forecasting/long-short-term-memory] His supervisor, Jürgen Schmidhuber, considered the thesis highly significant.
[src:time-series-forecasting/long-short-term-memory] An early version of LSTM was published in 1995 in a technical report by Sepp Hochreiter and Jürgen Schmidhuber, then published in the NIPS 1996 conference.
[src:time-series-forecasting/long-short-term-memory] The most commonly used reference point for LSTM was published in 1997 in the journal Neural Computation.
[src:time-series-forecasting/long-short-term-memory] By introducing Constant Error Carousel (CEC) units, LSTM deals with the vanishing gradient problem.
[src:time-series-forecasting/long-short-term-memory] The initial version of LSTM block included cells, input and output gates.
[src:time-series-forecasting/long-short-term-memory] Felix Gers, Jürgen Schmidhuber, and Fred Cummins introduced the forget gate (also called "keep gate") into the LSTM architecture in 1999, enabling the LSTM to reset its own state.
[src:time-series-forecasting/long-short-term-memory] This is the most commonly used version of LSTM nowadays.
[src:time-series-forecasting/long-short-term-memory] They added peephole connections in 2000.
[src:time-series-forecasting/long-short-term-memory] Additionally, the output activation function was omitted.
[src:time-series-forecasting/long-short-term-memory] In 2005 Graves and Schmidhuber published LSTM with full backpropagation through time and bidirectional LSTM.
[src:time-series-forecasting/long-short-term-memory] In 2006 Graves, Fernandez, Gomez, and Schmidhuber introduced a new error function for LSTM: Connectionist Temporal Classification (CTC) for simultaneous alignment and recognition of sequences.
[src:time-series-forecasting/long-short-term-memory] In 2014 Kyunghyun Cho an others published a simplified variant of the forget gate LSTM called Gated recurrent unit (GRU).
[src:time-series-forecasting/long-short-term-memory] In 2015 Srivastava, Greff, and Schmidhuber used LSTM principles to create the Highway network, a feedforward neural network with hundreds of layers, much deeper than previous networks.
[src:time-series-forecasting/long-short-term-memory] Concurrently, the ResNet architecture was developed.
[src:time-series-forecasting/long-short-term-memory] It is equivalent to an open-gated or gateless highway network.
[src:time-series-forecasting/long-short-term-memory] A modern upgrade of LSTM called xLSTM is published by a team led by Sepp Hochreiter.
[src:time-series-forecasting/long-short-term-memory] One of the 2 blocks (mLSTM) of the architecture are parallelizable like the Transformer architecture, the other ones (sLSTM) allow state tracking.
[src:time-series-forecasting/long-short-term-memory] Hochreiter et al. used LSTM for meta-learning (i.e. learning a learning algorithm).
[src:time-series-forecasting/long-short-term-memory] Mayer et al. trained LSTM to control robots.
[src:time-series-forecasting/long-short-term-memory] Hochreiter, Heuesel, and Obermayr applied LSTM to protein homology detection the field of biology.
[src:time-series-forecasting/seasonality] In time series data, **seasonality** refers to the trends that occur at specific regular intervals less than a year, such as weekly, monthly, or quarterly.
[src:time-series-forecasting/seasonality] Seasonality may be caused by various factors, such as weather, vacation, and holidays and consists of periodic, repetitive, and generally regular and predictable patterns in the levels of a time series.
[src:time-series-forecasting/seasonality] Seasonal fluctuations in a time series can be contrasted with cyclical patterns.
[src:time-series-forecasting/seasonality] The latter occur when the data exhibits rises and falls that are not of a fixed period.
[src:time-series-forecasting/seasonality] Such non-seasonal fluctuations are usually due to economic conditions and are often related to the "business cycle"; their period usually extends beyond a single year, and the fluctuations are usually of at least two years.
[src:time-series-forecasting/seasonality] Organisations facing seasonal variations, such as ice-cream vendors, are often interested in knowing their performance relative to the normal seasonal variation.
[src:time-series-forecasting/seasonality] Seasonal variations in the labour market can be attributed to the entrance of school leavers into the job market as they aim to contribute to the workforce upon the completion of their schooling.
[src:time-series-forecasting/seasonality] These regular changes are of less interest to those who study employment data than the variations that occur due to the underlying state of the economy; their focus is on how unemployment in the workforce has changed, despite the impact of the regular seasonal variations.
[src:time-series-forecasting/seasonality] It is necessary for organisations to identify and measure seasonal variations within their market to help them plan for the future.
[src:time-series-forecasting/seasonality] This can prepare them for the temporary increases or decreases in labour requirements and inventory as demand for their product or service fluctuates over certain periods.
[src:time-series-forecasting/seasonality] This may require training, periodic maintenance, and so forth that can be organized in advance.
[src:time-series-forecasting/seasonality] Apart from these considerations, the organisations need to know if variation they have experienced has been more or less than the expected amount, beyond what the usual seasonal variations account for.
[src:time-series-forecasting/seasonality] A really good way to find periodicity, including seasonality, in any regular series of data is to remove any overall trend first and then to inspect time periodicity.
[src:time-series-forecasting/seasonality] The run sequence plot is a recommended first step for analyzing any time series.
[src:time-series-forecasting/seasonality] Although seasonality can sometimes be indicated by this plot, seasonality is shown more clearly by the seasonal subseries plot or the box plot.
[src:time-series-forecasting/seasonality] The seasonal subseries plot does an excellent job of showing both the seasonal differences (between group patterns) and also the within-group patterns.
[src:time-series-forecasting/seasonality] The box plot shows the seasonal difference (between group patterns) quite well, but it does not show within group patterns.
[src:time-series-forecasting/seasonality] However, for large data sets, the box plot is usually easier to read than the seasonal subseries plot.
[src:time-series-forecasting/seasonality] The seasonal plot, seasonal subseries plot, and the box plot all assume that the seasonal periods are known.
[src:time-series-forecasting/seasonality] In most cases, the analyst will in fact, know this.
[src:time-series-forecasting/seasonality] For example, for monthly data, the period is 12 since there are 12 months in a year.
[src:time-series-forecasting/seasonality] However, if the period is not known, the autocorrelation plot can help.
[src:time-series-forecasting/seasonality] If there is significant seasonality, the autocorrelation plot should show spikes at lags equal to the period.
[src:time-series-forecasting/seasonality] For example, for monthly data, if there is a seasonality effect, we would expect to see significant peaks at lag 12, 24, 36, and so on (although the intensity may decrease the further out we go).
[src:time-series-forecasting/seasonality] An autocorrelation plot (ACF) can be used to identify seasonality, as it calculates the difference (residual amount) between a Y value and a lagged value of Y.
[src:time-series-forecasting/seasonality] The result gives some points where the two values are close together ( no seasonality ), but other points where there is a large discrepancy.
[src:time-series-forecasting/seasonality] These points indicate a level of seasonality in the data.
[src:time-series-forecasting/seasonality] Semiregular cyclic variations might be dealt with by spectral density estimation.
[src:time-series-forecasting/seasonality] Seasonal variation is measured in terms of an index, called a seasonal index.
[src:time-series-forecasting/seasonality] It is an average that can be used to compare an actual observation relative to what it would be if there were no seasonal variation.
[src:time-series-forecasting/seasonality] An index value is attached to each period of the time series within a year.
[src:time-series-forecasting/seasonality] This implies that if monthly data are considered there are 12 separate seasonal indices, one for each month.
[src:time-series-forecasting/seasonality] The following methods use seasonal indices to measure seasonal variations of a time-series data.
[src:time-series-forecasting/seasonality] The measurement of seasonal variation by using the ratio-to-moving-average method provides an index to measure the degree of the seasonal variation in a time series.
[src:time-series-forecasting/seasonality] The index is based on a mean of 100, with the degree of seasonality measured by variations away from the base.
[src:time-series-forecasting/seasonality] For example, if we observe the hotel rentals in a winter resort, we find that the winter quarter index is 124.
[src:time-series-forecasting/seasonality] The value 124 indicates that 124 percent of the average quarterly rental occur in winter.
[src:time-series-forecasting/seasonality] If the hotel management records 1436 rentals for the whole of last year, then the average quarterly rental would be 359= (1436/4).
[src:time-series-forecasting/seasonality] Here, 359 is the average quarterly rental.
[src:time-series-forecasting/seasonality] 445 the seasonalized winter-quarter rental.
[src:time-series-forecasting/seasonality] This method is also called the percentage moving average method.
[src:time-series-forecasting/seasonality] In this method, the original data values in the time-series are expressed as percentages of moving averages.
[src:time-series-forecasting/seasonality] The steps and the tabulations are given below.
[src:time-series-forecasting/seasonality] Express each original data value of the time-series as a percentage of the corresponding centered moving average values obtained in step(1).
[src:time-series-forecasting/seasonality] In other words, in a multiplicative time-series model, we get (Original data values) / (Trend values) × 100 = (T × C × S × I) / (T × C) × 100 = (S × I ) × 100.
[src:time-series-forecasting/seasonality] This implies that the ratio-to-moving average represents the seasonal and irregular components.
[src:time-series-forecasting/seasonality] Arrange these percentages according to months or quarter of given years.
[src:time-series-forecasting/seasonality] Find the averages over all months or quarters of the given years.
[src:time-series-forecasting/seasonality] If the sum of these indices is not 1200 (or 400 for quarterly figures), multiply then by a correction factor = 1200 / (sum of monthly indices).
[src:time-series-forecasting/seasonality] Otherwise, the 12 monthly averages will be considered as seasonal indices.
[src:time-series-forecasting/seasonality] Now calculations for 4 quarterly moving averages and ratio-to-moving-averages are shown in the below table.
[src:time-series-forecasting/seasonality] Now the total of seasonal averages is 398.85.
[src:time-series-forecasting/seasonality] Therefore, the corresponding correction factor would be 400/398.85 = 1.00288.
[src:time-series-forecasting/seasonality] Each seasonal average is multiplied by the correction factor 1.00288 to get the adjusted seasonal indices as shown in the above table.
[src:time-series-forecasting/seasonality] However, in practice the detrending of time-series is done to arrive at $S\cdot C\cdot I$ .
[src:time-series-forecasting/seasonality] This is done by dividing both sides of $Y=T\cdot S\cdot C\cdot I$ by trend values T so that ${\frac {Y}{T}}=S\cdot C\cdot I$ .
[src:time-series-forecasting/seasonality] A completely regular cyclic variation in a time series might be dealt with in time series analysis by using a sinusoidal model with one or more sinusoids whose period-lengths may be known or unknown depending on the context.
[src:time-series-forecasting/seasonality] A less completely regular cyclic variation might be dealt with by using a special form of an ARIMA model which can be structured so as to treat cyclic variations semi-explicitly.
[src:time-series-forecasting/seasonality] Such models represent cyclostationary processes.
[src:time-series-forecasting/seasonality] Another method of modelling periodic seasonality is the use of pairs of Fourier terms.
[src:time-series-forecasting/seasonality] Similar to using the sinusoidal model, Fourier terms added into regression models utilize sine and cosine terms in order to simulate seasonality.
[src:time-series-forecasting/seasonality] However, the seasonality of such a regression would be represented as the sum of sine or cosine terms, instead of a single sine or cosine term in a sinusoidal model.
[src:time-series-forecasting/seasonality] Every periodic function can be approximated with the inclusion of Fourier terms.
[src:time-series-forecasting/seasonality] If it is a multiplicative model, the magnitude of the seasonal fluctuations will vary with the level, which is more likely to occur with economic series.
[src:time-series-forecasting/seasonality] When taking seasonality into account, the seasonally adjusted multiplicative decomposition can be written as $Y_{t}/S_{t}=T_{t}*E_{t}$ ; whereby the original time series is divided by the estimated seasonal component.
[src:time-series-forecasting/seasonality] One particular implementation of seasonal adjustment is provided by X-12-ARIMA.
[src:time-series-forecasting/seasonality] Each dummy variable is set to 1 if the data point is drawn from the dummy's specified season and 0 otherwise.
[src:time-series-forecasting/seasonality] Then the predicted value of the dependent variable for the reference season is computed from the rest of the regression, while for any other season it is computed using the rest of the regression and by inserting the value 1 for the dummy variable for that season.
[src:time-series-forecasting/seasonality] It is important to distinguish seasonal patterns from related patterns.
[src:time-series-forecasting/seasonality] While a **seasonal pattern** occurs when a time series is affected by the season or the time of the year, such as annual, semiannual, quarterly, etc.
[src:time-series-forecasting/seasonality] A **cyclic pattern**, or simply a **cycle**, occurs when the data exhibit rises and falls in other periods, i.e., much longer (e.g., decadal) or much shorter (e.g., weekly) than seasonal.
[src:time-series-forecasting/seasonality] A **quasiperiodicity** is a more general, irregular periodicity.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] In mathematics, a **time series** is a sequence of data points indexed, listed, or graphed in chronological order.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] Most commonly, a time series consists of observations recorded at successive equally spaced points in time.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] Thus, it represents a form of discrete-time data.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] A time series may describe measurements collected over seconds, days, years, or even centuries.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] Common examples include heights of ocean tides, counts of sunspots, daily temperature readings, and the closing values of stock market indices such as the Dow Jones Industrial Average.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] A time series is often visualized using a run chart (a type of temporal line chart), which helps identify patterns such as trends, seasonal effects, and irregular fluctuations.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] Time series data have a natural temporal ordering.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] This makes time series analysis distinct from cross-sectional studies, in which there is no natural ordering of the observations (e.g. explaining people's wages by reference to their respective education levels, where the individuals' data could be entered in any order).
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] Time series analysis is also distinct from spatial data analysis where the observations typically relate to geographical locations (e.g. accounting for house prices by the location as well as the intrinsic characteristics of the houses).
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] A stochastic model for a time series will generally reflect the fact that observations close together in time will be more closely related than observations further apart.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] In addition, time series models will often make use of the natural one-way ordering of time so that values for a given period will be expressed as deriving in some way from past values, rather than from future values (see time reversibility).
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] Time series analysis can be applied to real-valued, continuous data, discrete numeric data, or discrete symbolic data (i.e. sequences of characters, such as letters and words in the English language).
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] Methods for time series analysis may be divided into two classes: frequency-domain methods and time-domain methods.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] The former include spectral analysis and wavelet analysis; the latter include auto-correlation and cross-correlation analysis.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] In the time domain, correlation and analysis can be made in a filter-like manner using scaled correlation, thereby mitigating the need to operate in the frequency domain.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] Additionally, time series analysis techniques may be divided into parametric and non-parametric methods.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] The parametric approaches assume that the underlying stationary stochastic process has a certain structure which can be described using a small number of parameters (for example, using an autoregressive or moving-average model).
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] In these approaches, the task is to estimate the parameters of the model that describes the stochastic process.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] By contrast, non-parametric approaches explicitly estimate the covariance or the spectrum of the process without assuming that the process has any particular structure.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] Methods of time series analysis may also be divided into linear and non-linear, and univariate and multivariate.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] A time series is one type of panel data.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] Panel data is the general class, a multidimensional data set, whereas a time series data set is a one-dimensional panel (as is a cross-sectional dataset).
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] A data set may exhibit characteristics of both panel data and time series data.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] One way to tell is to ask what makes one data record unique from the other records.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] If the answer is the time data field, then this is a time series data set candidate.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] If determining a unique record requires a time data field and an additional identifier which is unrelated to time (e.g. student ID, stock symbol, country code), then it is panel data candidate.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] If the differentiation lies on the non-time identifier, then the data set is a cross-sectional data set candidate.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] There are several types of motivation and data analysis available for time series which are appropriate for different purposes.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] In the context of statistics, econometrics, quantitative finance, seismology, meteorology, and geophysics the primary goal of time series analysis is forecasting.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] In the context of signal processing, control engineering and communication engineering it is used for signal detection.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] Other applications are in data mining, pattern recognition and machine learning, where time series analysis can be used for clustering, classification, query by content, anomaly detection as well as forecasting.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] A simple way to examine a regular time series is manually with a line chart.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] The datagraphic shows tuberculosis deaths in the United States, along with the yearly change and the percentage change from year to year.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] The total number of deaths declined in every year until the mid-1980s, after which there were occasional increases, often proportionately - but not absolutely - quite large.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] A study of corporate data analysts found two challenges to exploratory time series analysis: discovering the shape of interesting patterns, and finding an explanation for these patterns.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] Visual tools that represent time series data as heat map matrices can help overcome these challenges.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] This approach may be based on harmonic analysis and filtering of signals in the frequency domain using the Fourier transform, and spectral density estimation.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] Its development was significantly accelerated during World War II by mathematician Norbert Wiener, electrical engineers Rudolf E.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] Kálmán, Dennis Gabor and others for filtering signals from noise and predicting signal values at a certain point in time.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] An equivalent effect may be achieved in the time domain, as in a Kalman filter; see filtering and smoothing for more techniques.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] Curve fitting is the process of constructing a curve, or mathematical function, that has the best fit to a series of data points, possibly subject to constraints.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] Curve fitting can involve either interpolation, where an exact fit to the data is required, or smoothing, in which a "smooth" function is constructed that approximately fits the data.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] A related topic is regression analysis, which focuses more on questions of statistical inference such as how much uncertainty is present in a curve that is fit to data observed with random errors.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] Fitted curves can be used as an aid for data visualization, to infer values of a function where no data are available, and to summarize the relationships among two or more variables.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] Extrapolation refers to the use of a fitted curve beyond the range of the observed data, and is subject to a degree of uncertainty since it may reflect the method used to construct the curve as much as it reflects the observed data.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] For processes that are expected to generally grow in magnitude one of the curves in the graphic (and many others) can be fitted by estimating their parameters.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] The construction of economic time series involves the estimation of some components for some dates by interpolation between values ("benchmarks") for earlier and later dates.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] Interpolation is estimation of an unknown quantity between two known quantities (historical data), or drawing conclusions about missing information from the available information ("reading between the lines").
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] Interpolation is useful where the data surrounding the missing data is available and its trend, seasonality, and longer-term cycles are known.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] This is often done by using a related series known for all relevant dates.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] Alternatively polynomial interpolation or spline interpolation is used where piecewise polynomial functions are fitted in time intervals such that they fit smoothly together.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] A different problem which is closely related to interpolation is the approximation of a complicated function by a simple function (also called regression).
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] The main difference between regression and interpolation is that polynomial regression gives a single polynomial that models the entire data set.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] Spline interpolation, however, yield a piecewise continuous function composed of many polynomials to model the data set.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] Extrapolation is the process of estimating, beyond the original observation range, the value of a variable on the basis of its relationship with another variable.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] It is similar to interpolation, which produces estimates between known observations, but extrapolation is subject to greater uncertainty and a higher risk of producing meaningless results.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] In general, a function approximation problem asks us to select a function among a well-defined class that closely matches ("approximates") a target function in a task-specific way.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] Second, the target function, call it *g*, may be unknown; instead of an explicit formula, only a set of points (a time series) of the form (*x*, *g*(*x*)) is provided.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] Depending on the structure of the domain and codomain of *g*, several techniques for approximating *g* may be applicable.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] For example, if *g* is an operation on the real numbers, techniques of interpolation, extrapolation, regression analysis, and curve fitting can be used.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] If the codomain (range or target set) of *g* is a finite set, one is dealing with a classification problem instead.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] A related problem of *online* time series approximation is to summarize the data in one-pass and construct an approximate representation that can support a variety of time series queries with bounds on worst-case error.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] To some extent, the different problems (regression, classification, fitness approximation) have received a unified treatment in statistical learning theory, where they are viewed as supervised learning problems.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] In statistics, prediction is a part of statistical inference.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] One particular approach to such inference is known as predictive inference, but the prediction can be undertaken within any of the several approaches to statistical inference.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] Indeed, one description of statistics is that it provides a means of transferring knowledge about a sample of a population to the whole population, and to other related populations, which is not necessarily the same as prediction over time.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] When information is transferred across time, often to specific points in time, the process is known as forecasting.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] Assigning time series pattern to a specific category, for example identify a word based on series of hand movements in sign language.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] Splitting a time-series into a sequence of segments.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] It is often the case that a time-series can be represented as a sequence of individual segments, each with its own characteristic properties.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] For example, the audio signal from a conference call can be partitioned into pieces corresponding to the times during which each person was speaking.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] In time-series segmentation, the goal is to identify the segment boundary points in the time-series, and to characterize the dynamical properties associated with each segment.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] One can approach this problem using change-point detection, or by modeling the time-series as a more sophisticated system, such as a Markov jump linear system.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] Time series data may be clustered, however special care has to be taken when considering subsequence clustering.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] Subsequence time series clustering resulted in unstable (random) clusters *induced by the feature extraction* using chunking with sliding windows.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] It was found that the cluster centers (the average of the time series in a cluster - also a time series) follow an arbitrarily shifted sine pattern (regardless of the dataset, even on realizations of a random walk).
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] This means that the found cluster centers are non-descriptive for the dataset because the cluster centers are always nonrepresentative sine waves.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] Models for time series data can have many forms and represent different stochastic processes.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] When modeling variations in the level of a process, three broad classes of practical importance are the *autoregressive* (AR) models, the *integrated* (I) models, and the *moving-average* (MA) models.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] These three classes depend *linearly* on previous data points.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] Combinations of these ideas produce autoregressive moving-average (ARMA) and autoregressive integrated moving-average (ARIMA) models.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] The autoregressive fractionally integrated moving-average (ARFIMA) model generalizes the former three.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] Another important generalization is the time-varying autoregressive (TVAR) model, in which the AR coefficients are allowed to change over time, enabling the model to capture evolving or non-stationary dynamics.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] Extensions of these classes to deal with vector-valued data are available under the heading of multivariate time-series models and sometimes the preceding acronyms are extended by including an initial "V" for "vector", as in VAR for vector autoregression.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] For these models, the acronyms are extended with a final "X" for "exogenous".
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] Time-varying autoregressive (TVAR) models are especially useful for analyzing non-stationary time series in which the underlying dynamics evolve over time in complex ways, not limited to classical forms of variation such as trends or seasonal patterns.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] This flexibility makes them well suited to modeling structural changes, regime shifts, or gradual evolutions in a system's behavior.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] Estimation of TVAR models typically involves methods such as kernel smoothing, recursive least squares, or Kalman filtering.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] Non-linear dependence of the level of a series on previous data points is of interest, partly because of the possibility of producing a chaotic time series.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] However, more importantly, empirical investigations can indicate the advantage of using predictions derived from non-linear models, over those from linear models, as for example in nonlinear autoregressive exogenous models.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] Among other types of non-linear time series models, there are models to represent the changes of variance over time (heteroskedasticity).
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] These models represent autoregressive conditional heteroskedasticity (ARCH) and the collection comprises a wide variety of representation (GARCH, TARCH, EGARCH, FIGARCH, CGARCH, etc.).
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] Here changes in variability are related to, or predicted by, recent past values of the observed series.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] This is in contrast to other possible representations of locally varying variability, where the variability might be modeled as being driven by a separate time-varying process, as in a doubly stochastic model.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] Multiscale (often referred to as multiresolution) techniques decompose a given time series, attempting to illustrate time dependence at multiple scales.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] See also Markov switching multifractal (MSMF) techniques for modeling volatility evolution.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] A hidden Markov model (HMM) is a statistical Markov model in which the system being modeled is assumed to be a Markov process with unobserved (hidden) states.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] An HMM can be considered as the simplest dynamic Bayesian network.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] HMM models are widely used in speech recognition, for translating a time series of spoken words into text.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] Many of these models are collected in the python package sktime.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] A number of different notations are in use for time-series analysis.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] Ergodicity implies stationarity, but the converse is not necessarily the case.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] Stationarity is usually classified into strict stationarity and wide-sense or second-order stationarity.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] Both models and applications can be developed under each of these conditions, although the models in the latter case might be considered as only partly specified.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] In addition, time-series analysis can be applied where the series are seasonally stationary or non-stationary.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] Situations where the amplitudes of frequency components change with time can be dealt with in time-frequency analysis which makes use of a time–frequency representation of a time-series or signal.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] Time series can be visualized with two categories of chart: Overlapping Charts and Separated Charts.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] Jevons was the first to study times series.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] In his book he examined a number of weekly financial time series between the years 1825 to 1860 inclusive.
[src:time-series-forecasting/time-series] These included times series of bankruptcies, currency circulation and discount rates.
